type="local"
href="jms-00I7.xml"
addr="jms-00I7"
title="Relation">relation</fr:link></fr:strong></fr:em> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {id}_{A}\colon  A\mathbin {\nrightarrow } A]]></fr:tex>, also called the <fr:em><fr:strong>equality <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00I7.xml"
addr="jms-00I7"
title="Relation">relation</fr:link></fr:strong></fr:em>, which relates each element of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to itself. In other words, we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a\mathrel {\mathsf {id}_{A}} a']]></fr:tex> if and only if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a=a']]></fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:p>We have already seen the <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00I9.xml"
addr="jms-00I9"
title="Relations in program specification">square root relation from positive reals to reals</fr:link>, which corresponds to a <fr:em>total</fr:em> but <fr:em>many-valued</fr:em> function. We can define an analogous relationship in <fr:ref
addr="jms-00IJ"
href="jms-00IJ.xml"
taxon="Example" /> below from positive integers (naturals) to integers, which will correspond to a <fr:em>partial</fr:em> and many-valued function.</fr:p><fr:tree
